  <h2>The Problem with Shipping</h2>

  <p>
    Here's a scenario that plays out constantly: a boat's in a marina in Nova Scotia. Something breaks — a bracket, a fitting, a custom mount. The skipper needs it fixed before the tide window closes or the next race starts. Shipping a part from our shop takes two days minimum. That's two days the boat doesn't move.
  </p>

  <p>
    So we stopped waiting for the problem to come to us. We go to the problem.
  </p>

  <h2>What Field Deployment Looks Like</h2>

  <p>
    I pack a Prusa MK4 or CORE One into a Pelican case with filament, tools, a laptop, and a power setup. I fly, drive, or ferry to wherever the client is. I set up the printer on-site — could be a dock, a garage, a workshop, a race paddock — and I print what's needed right there.
  </p>

  <p>
    The client gets to watch the part come to life. They can check the fit in real-time. If it needs adjustment, we adjust, reprint, and iterate on the spot. No back-and-forth shipping, no guessing on measurements, no delays.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Marinas:</strong> Parts printed dockside, fit-checked on the boat immediately.</li>
    <li><strong>Race events:</strong> Broken brackets, aero components, or mounts reprinted between sessions.</li>
    <li><strong>Remote locations:</strong> Industrial sites, research stations, or vessels where overnight shipping isn't an option.</li>
    <li><strong>Festivals and demos:</strong> Live printing at events shows people what's possible.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why It Works</h2>

  <p>
    3D printers are portable. That sounds obvious, but the industry hasn't caught up to this idea yet. Most print shops are stationary — you send them a file, they send you a part. That works fine for non-urgent, non-critical applications.
  </p>

  <p>
    But when you need a part <em>now</em>, at a <em>specific location</em>, the traditional model falls apart. Field deployment is manufacturing on demand, at the point of need. It's the same logic behind mobile welding services — the welder goes to the broken thing, not the other way around.
  </p>

  <p>
    My background in the RV helps here. I've already run printers off generators, in unstable power environments, in heat and humidity. I know what it takes to get reliable prints outside a climate-controlled shop. That experience is baked into the service.
  </p>

  <h2>Events and Demonstrations</h2>

  <p>
    Field deployment isn't always about emergencies. We also bring printers to events — boat shows, car meets, maker faires, trade shows. People gather around a running printer like it's a campfire. They watch a part materialize and suddenly 3D printing isn't abstract anymore. It's real, it's accessible, and they start thinking about their own problems it could solve.
  </p>

  <p>
    These events are some of my favorite work. Talking to people about what we do, showing them the materials, letting them hold a finished part and feel the difference between PLA and ASA. That hands-on experience sells the concept better than any website ever could.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Costs</h2>

  <p>
    Field deployment includes travel, setup, materials, and my time on-site. It's not cheap compared to a mail-order print — you're paying for the immediacy and the expertise. But when the alternative is a boat missing its weather window, a race car sitting out a session, or equipment sitting idle waiting for a part from overseas, the math works out fast.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you've got a situation where waiting isn't an option, <a href="/contact">reach out</a>. Tell me where you are, what you need, and when you need it. We'll make it happen.
  </p>
